This is a show where
we explore the mysteries

00:00:20.686 --> 00:00:23.756 align:start size:88% position:13% line:83%
and the science of
the amazing human brain.

00:00:23.857 --> 00:00:26.392 line:83%
Jamie Dupree has been a
radio news correspondent

00:00:26.492 --> 00:00:28.027 line:92%
for over 30 years.

00:00:28.127 --> 00:00:30.196
He's covered politics
in our nation's capital

00:00:30.296 --> 00:00:31.831
most of that time.

00:00:31.931 --> 00:00:35.268 align:start size:84% position:16%
And then two years ago,
he lost his voice.

00:00:35.368 --> 00:00:37.870 align:start size:88% position:13%
The very tool that
helped him make a living.

00:00:37.970 --> 00:00:39.939 align:start size:88% position:13%
Since then,
he has been on a journey

00:00:40.039 --> 00:00:43.243 align:start size:84% position:16%
to get his voice,
and his old life, back.

00:00:44.510 --> 00:00:45.678 line:92%
<i> Let me say it this way,</i>

00:00:45.778 --> 00:00:49.515 align:start position:0% line:91%
<i>I think Chairman Gowdy's
initial assessment is accurate.</i>

00:00:49.615 --> 00:00:53.486 align:start size:91% position:9% line:88%
<i> (Jaye Watson)
 When you've done something
 for 32 years,</i>

00:00:53.586 --> 00:00:55.955
<i> there's an automatic rhythm,</i>

00:00:56.055 --> 00:00:58.591 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> one in which your feet
 know the way,</i>

00:00:58.691 --> 00:01:01.327 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> because they've walked
 these sidewalks,</i>

00:01:01.427 --> 00:01:05.798
<i> these stairs,
 these hallways</i>

00:01:05.898 --> 00:01:08.500
<i> thousands of times.</i>

00:01:08.601 --> 00:01:10.703
<i> It is this familiar
 routine in a career</i>

00:01:10.803 --> 00:01:14.239 align:start size:81% position:19%
<i> that breeds expertise
 and burnout.</i>

00:01:14.339 --> 00:01:15.975 line:0%
<i> In Jamie Dupree's case,</i>

00:01:16.075 --> 00:01:19.511 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
<i> all he has ever wanted to do
 is exactly this.</i>

00:01:19.612 --> 00:01:20.980 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
...we'll be digging through
all the details

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:22.381 line:0%
on healthcare reform.

00:01:22.481 --> 00:01:24.317 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
<i> (Jaye Watson)
 A radio news correspondent
 for Cox Radio,</i>

00:01:24.417 --> 00:01:26.085 line:0%
<i> based in Washington D.C.</i>

00:01:26.185 --> 00:01:27.220 align:start size:69% position:31% line:83%
...that I didn't think
he needed to do.

00:01:26.185 --> 00:01:27.220 align:start position:0%
Right.

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:28.454 align:start size:44% position:56%
He should just
let it go.

00:01:28.554 --> 00:01:29.689
<i> (Donald Trump)
 Thank you all
 for being here.</i>

00:01:29.789 --> 00:01:31.157
<i> This is, uh...</i>

00:01:31.257 --> 00:01:32.758 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> (Jaye Watson)
 Dupree has covered the
 United States Congress</i>

00:01:32.859 --> 00:01:35.728 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> and politics under
 six different presidents.</i>

00:01:37.930 --> 00:01:39.666 align:start size:94% position:6%
<i> In the basement of
 the Russell Federal Building,</i>

00:01:39.766 --> 00:01:42.168 align:start size:94% position:6%
<i> Dupree and other journalists
 await politicians'</i>

00:01:42.268 --> 00:01:44.804
<i> coming and going
 from the Capitol.</i>

00:01:44.904 --> 00:01:46.171 align:start size:59% position:41%
I haven't looked at
the information,

00:01:46.272 --> 00:01:47.640 align:start size:38% position:63%
but I have--

00:01:47.740 --> 00:01:50.243 align:start size:91% position:9%
<i> (Jaye)
 Dupree doesn't ask Senator
 Lindsey Graham a question,</i>

00:01:50.343 --> 00:01:52.112
<i> and this is why.</i>

00:01:53.913 --> 00:01:58.751 align:start size:69% position:31% line:0%
Every day, I-I get up,
and I hope

00:01:58.852 --> 00:02:05.958 align:start size:44% position:56% line:0%
that overnight
it is solved.

00:02:06.058 --> 00:02:07.360 align:start size:88% position:13% line:91%
<i> (Jaye)
 To and a half years ago,</i>

00:02:07.460 --> 00:02:10.363 align:start size:88% position:13% line:91%
<i> this 55-year-old
 married dad of three kids</i>

00:02:10.463 --> 00:02:12.031 line:92%
<i> lost his voice.</i>

00:02:12.131 --> 00:02:13.299 align:start position:0% line:91%
<i>(woman)
Last name, Dupree.</i>

00:02:13.399 --> 00:02:15.501 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> (Jaye)
 Two dozen experts
 and thousands of miles</i>

00:02:15.601 --> 00:02:17.369
<i> traveled around
 the country later,</i>

00:02:17.469 --> 00:02:19.305 align:start size:81% position:19%
<i> he is still
 searching for answers</i>

00:02:19.405 --> 00:02:21.707
<i> and treatment
 that will work.</i>

00:02:21.807 --> 00:02:26.278 align:start position:0%
Um, during the time,
it got worse,

00:02:26.378 --> 00:02:29.015 align:start position:0%
and worse, and worse.

00:02:29.115 --> 00:02:30.683 align:start size:75% position:25%
<i> (Jaye)
 Dupree has flown
 to Atlanta</i>

00:02:30.783 --> 00:02:32.752
<i> to see neurologist
 Dr. Hyder Jinnah</i>

00:02:32.852 --> 00:02:34.187
<i> at Emory Brain Health.</i>

00:02:34.287 --> 00:02:36.255 align:start size:56% position:44%
All right, good.
Open and close
your hands for me.

00:02:36.355 --> 00:02:37.389 align:start size:63% position:38%
Just walk naturally.

00:02:37.490 --> 00:02:38.724 align:start size:75% position:25%
Okay, I'm just gonna put
my finger on your chin.

00:02:38.824 --> 00:02:40.593 align:start size:56% position:44% line:83%
I'm gonna touch my
finger with this.

00:02:38.824 --> 00:02:40.593 align:start size:75% position:25%
Uh-huh.

00:02:40.693 --> 00:02:42.562 align:start size:56% position:44%
Touch your nose.
Go back and forth.

00:02:42.662 --> 00:02:43.829 align:start size:53% position:47%
Stop right there.

00:02:43.929 --> 00:02:47.266 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> (Jaye)
 Dupree does well on tests
 not involving speech.</i>

00:02:47.366 --> 00:02:48.734 align:start size:63% position:38%
<i> (Dr. Hyder Jinnah)
 Good. Come on back.</i>

00:02:48.834 --> 00:02:50.236 align:start size:66% position:34%
<i> I want you to say
 a few things for me.</i>

00:02:50.336 --> 00:02:51.637
<i> (laughing)</i>

00:02:51.738 --> 00:02:53.339 align:start size:50% position:50%
<i> We mow our lawn
 every year.</i>

00:02:53.439 --> 00:02:55.307 align:start position:0%
Yeah--
No. Um...

00:02:55.408 --> 00:02:57.210 align:start position:0%
<i>(laughing)</i>

00:02:57.310 --> 00:03:01.447 align:start position:0%
We mow our lawn
every year.

00:03:01.548 --> 00:03:04.817 align:start size:81% position:19% line:0%
<i> (Dr. Jinnah)
 He has a problem that
 falls in the category</i>

00:03:04.917 --> 00:03:07.487 line:0%
<i> of disorders known
 as the Dystonias.</i>

00:03:07.587 --> 00:03:09.822 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
Somehow, the brain
gets the signal wrong,

00:03:09.922 --> 00:03:12.492 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
and it sort of
overdoes the movement.

00:03:12.592 --> 00:03:14.893 align:start size:81% position:19% line:0%
So the muscles
contract too strong.

00:03:14.994 --> 00:03:16.662 line:0%
They occasionally
go into spasm.

00:03:16.762 --> 00:03:18.598 align:start position:0%
He had-had...

00:03:18.698 --> 00:03:20.466 align:start size:72% position:28%
<i> (Dr. Jinnah)
 Mr. Dupree,
 when he speaks,</i>

00:03:20.567 --> 00:03:23.268 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> his tongue is doing
 way more than it should.</i>

00:03:23.369 --> 00:03:24.603
It's contracting,
it's going up,

00:03:24.704 --> 00:03:26.372
it's going out,
it's going down,

00:03:26.472 --> 00:03:29.608 align:start size:88% position:13%
and it shouldn't
be doing all that stuff.

00:03:29.709 --> 00:03:32.511 align:start size:91% position:9%
<i> (Jaye)
 Dystonia is the third most
 common movement disorder</i>

00:03:32.611 --> 00:03:35.214
<i> behind tremor and
 Parkinson's disease,</i>

00:03:35.314 --> 00:03:39.485 align:start size:94% position:6%
<i> but Jamie's dystonia is rare
 and difficult to treat.</i>

00:03:39.585 --> 00:03:41.420 align:start size:81% position:19%
<i> Scientists know that
 dystonia begins</i>

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:42.688
<i> in the regions
 of the brain</i>

00:03:42.788 --> 00:03:44.857 align:start size:75% position:25%
<i> involved
 movement control.</i>

00:03:44.957 --> 00:03:48.161 align:start size:91% position:9% line:76%
<i> This motor circuit
 includes the motor cortex,</i>

00:03:48.261 --> 00:03:50.796 align:start size:78% position:22% line:76%
<i> cerebellum,
 and basal ganglia.</i>

00:03:50.896 --> 00:03:54.033 line:76%
<i> Exactly where dystonia
 begins is not known.</i>

00:03:56.135 --> 00:03:57.303
<i> It can be genetic,</i>

00:03:57.403 --> 00:03:59.606 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> and sometimes triggered
 by an event.</i>

00:03:59.706 --> 00:04:01.974
<i> In Jamie's case, he got
 sick on a family vacation</i>

00:04:02.074 --> 00:04:05.211 align:start size:97% position:3%
<i> to England, and says
 it morphed into a heart event,</i>

00:04:05.311 --> 00:04:08.013
<i> an a trip to the ER
 when he got back home.</i>

00:04:08.113 --> 00:04:11.184 align:start size:81% position:19%
<i> After that,
 his voice faded away.</i>

00:04:11.284 --> 00:04:14.620 align:start size:91% position:9%
We believe that it's
something you were born with,

00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:18.324 align:start size:72% position:28%
a tendency
to be at risk for this.

00:04:18.424 --> 00:04:19.926 align:start size:66% position:34%
But you weren't gonna
develop the problem

00:04:20.026 --> 00:04:21.928 align:start size:66% position:34%
until you got exposed
to something else,

00:04:22.028 --> 00:04:23.930 align:start size:66% position:34% line:83%
which could have been
that virus.

00:04:22.028 --> 00:04:23.930 align:start size:78% position:22%
Mm-hmm.

00:04:24.030 --> 00:04:26.131 align:start size:59% position:41%
And then those
two things together

00:04:26.231 --> 00:04:29.268 size:78% position:61%
are what triggered the
evolution of the problem,

00:04:29.368 --> 00:04:31.604 align:start size:66% position:34%
so it's not the virus
by itself.

00:04:31.704 --> 00:04:34.674 align:start size:91% position:9%
<i> (Jaye)
 People like Dupree,
 who use their voice a lot,</i>

00:04:34.774 --> 00:04:37.509 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> develop this type
 of dystonia more often.</i>

00:04:37.609 --> 00:04:39.311 align:start size:75% position:25%
<i> Again, it's a bit
 of a mystery,</i>

00:04:39.411 --> 00:04:41.814 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> but it's something about
 repetitive use</i>

00:04:41.914 --> 00:04:45.184 align:start size:91% position:9%
<i> that can predispose things
 to go awry.</i>

00:04:45.284 --> 00:04:47.319 align:start size:75% position:25%
<i> An expert patient
 at this point,</i>

00:04:47.419 --> 00:04:49.989 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> Dupree asked Dr. Jinnah
 for the bottom line.</i>

00:04:50.089 --> 00:04:51.090 align:start size:16% position:84%
Yeah.

00:04:51.190 --> 00:04:52.992 align:start size:44% position:56%
Yeah, so the
bottom line...

00:04:53.092 --> 00:04:55.261 align:start size:72% position:28%
The bottom line is that
I would call this

00:04:55.361 --> 00:04:56.629 align:start size:63% position:38%
a segmental dystonia

00:04:56.729 --> 00:04:58.831 align:start size:59% position:41%
that involves your-
your voice box,

00:04:58.931 --> 00:05:00.333 align:start size:41% position:59%
your pharynx,
and probably

00:05:00.433 --> 00:05:02.434 align:start size:53% position:47%
your tongue
and lips as well.

00:05:02.535 --> 00:05:05.605 align:start size:72% position:28%
Uh, and this problem is
challenging to treat

00:05:05.705 --> 00:05:08.607 align:start size:56% position:44%
with any of the
available options.

00:05:08.707 --> 00:05:10.976 align:start size:59% position:41%
These options would
include medicines,

00:05:11.077 --> 00:05:13.445 align:start size:41% position:59%
and there are
a few others
we could try.

00:05:13.545 --> 00:05:16.649 align:start size:81% position:19%
Botulinum toxin injections
into the tongue,

00:05:16.749 --> 00:05:19.986 align:start size:63% position:38%
uh, and deep brain
stimulation surgery.

00:05:20.086 --> 00:05:21.854 align:start size:84% position:16%
So those are the three
options that we would have.

00:05:25.290 --> 00:05:28.794 align:start size:91% position:9%
<i> (Jaye)
 Dupree opts to have
 botulinum toxin injections.</i>

00:05:28.894 --> 00:05:32.165 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> The most common botulinum
 toxin is botox.</i>

00:05:32.265 --> 00:05:34.166 align:start size:81% position:19%
<i> The injections
 will be in his tongue</i>

00:05:34.267 --> 00:05:36.869 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> to try to relax and
 help with the thrusting.</i>

00:05:36.969 --> 00:05:38.404
Uh, it may help you...

00:05:38.504 --> 00:05:40.006 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> (Jaye)
 Dr. Jinnah has told him,</i>

00:05:40.106 --> 00:05:43.476 align:start size:91% position:9%
<i> his chances of improvement
 are 50% or less.</i>

00:05:43.576 --> 00:05:45.611 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> (Dr. Jinnah)
 But we certainly
 can't promise anything.</i>

00:05:45.711 --> 00:05:47.846 align:start size:88% position:13%
When it's in your tongue,
very hard to treat

00:05:47.946 --> 00:05:50.649 align:start size:91% position:9%
because the tongue is
such a complicated muscle.

00:05:50.750 --> 00:05:52.185
Uh, we don't think about
the tongue as a muscle,

00:05:52.285 --> 00:05:53.619
but it really is.

00:05:53.719 --> 00:05:55.388
It's a complicated muscle,

00:05:55.488 --> 00:05:58.857 align:start size:97% position:3%
uh, and so to get the medicine
exactly in the right place

00:05:58.957 --> 00:06:00.326 align:start size:75% position:25%
at the right dose
is hard.

00:06:00.426 --> 00:06:02.294 align:start position:0%
<i>(Jaye)
That just putting something
in there helps you speak?</i>

00:06:02.395 --> 00:06:03.595 align:start size:41% position:59%
Toothpick.

00:06:03.696 --> 00:06:05.097 align:start position:0%
<i>Toothpick.</i>

00:06:05.198 --> 00:06:06.331 align:start size:41% position:59%
Just one.

00:06:06.432 --> 00:06:09.268 align:start size:69% position:31%
You know, if I get in
there, it will sort of

00:06:09.368 --> 00:06:12.872 align:start size:72% position:28%
move stuff around,
and I can hold my mouth

00:06:12.972 --> 00:06:15.541 align:start size:69% position:31%
maybe a different way,

00:06:15.641 --> 00:06:17.676 align:start size:56% position:44%
and, uh,
a little more out.

00:06:17.776 --> 00:06:19.711 align:start position:0%
<i>But something larger
works even better?</i>

00:06:19.812 --> 00:06:21.780 align:start size:28% position:72%
Uh... no.

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:24.250 align:start position:0% line:85%
<i>Okay.</i>

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:24.250 align:start size:47% position:53%
Um, I can have,

00:06:24.350 --> 00:06:27.553 align:start size:78% position:22%
you know, that,
and hold onto my glasses.

00:06:27.653 --> 00:06:29.054 align:start size:34% position:66%
A little...

00:06:29.154 --> 00:06:31.256 align:start size:94% position:6%
<i> (Jaye)
 It's clear Dupree would
 prefer to be telling a story,</i>

00:06:31.357 --> 00:06:33.960 align:start size:78% position:22%
<i> not be the subject
 of it.</i>

00:06:34.060 --> 00:06:36.428 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> But privacy and
 Washington D.C. politics</i>

00:06:36.528 --> 00:06:38.197
<i> do not coexist.</i>

00:06:38.297 --> 00:06:41.467 align:start size:88% position:13% line:0%
<i> Dupree says he was deeply
 moved when lawmakers</i>

00:06:41.567 --> 00:06:44.169 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
<i> spoke of his struggle
 on the floor of the house.</i>

00:06:44.270 --> 00:06:46.138 line:0%
Mister speaker,
Jamie Dupree

00:06:46.238 --> 00:06:48.874 line:0%
is a perfect example
of the positive role

00:06:48.974 --> 00:06:51.243 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
that devoted
and professional journalists

00:06:51.343 --> 00:06:53.312 line:0%
play in our free society,

00:06:53.412 --> 00:06:55.881 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
