00:17:44.596 --> 00:17:47.532
<i> These students have had
 four years of med school,</i>

00:17:47.632 --> 00:17:49.935
<i> and are in the third
 of four more years</i>

00:17:50.035 --> 00:17:51.503 align:start size:78% position:22%
<i> of residency before
 they become</i>

00:17:51.603 --> 00:17:53.572
<i> full fledged
 psychiatrists.</i>

00:17:53.672 --> 00:17:56.474
<i> Theirs is a world of
 science, of research,</i>

00:17:56.575 --> 00:17:58.710 align:start size:72% position:28%
<i> of systems
 and diagnoses.</i>

00:17:58.810 --> 00:18:00.812 align:start position:0%
<i>(Dr. Andrew Furman)
The painting is a very
large painting</i>

00:18:00.912 --> 00:18:03.615 align:start position:0%
<i>of a slice of life
of the royal family.</i>

00:18:03.715 --> 00:18:07.652
It's a painting ostensibly of
the Infanta Margaret Theresa,

00:18:07.752 --> 00:18:09.220 align:start position:0%
who was at the time
of the painting,

00:18:09.321 --> 00:18:11.556 align:start position:0%
the only child
of King Philip IV

00:18:11.656 --> 00:18:13.391 align:start size:75% position:25%
and Queen Mariana
of Austria,

00:18:13.491 --> 00:18:15.494
<i> who were the king
 and queen of Spain.</i>

00:18:15.594 --> 00:18:17.328 align:start size:78% position:22%
<i> (Jaye)
 In psychiatrist,
 Dr. Andrew Furman's</i>

00:18:17.428 --> 00:18:21.500 align:start size:94% position:6%
<i> humanities based psychiatric
 case conference class,</i>

00:18:21.600 --> 00:18:24.936 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> art, music,
 and literature are used</i>

00:18:25.037 --> 00:18:27.940 align:start size:75% position:25%
<i> to breed a better
 physician.</i>

00:18:28.040 --> 00:18:32.110 align:start size:97% position:3%
A lot of what we do in our
education of future physicians

00:18:32.210 --> 00:18:33.811 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> is to help them
 understand the pathology</i>

00:18:33.912 --> 00:18:35.981 align:start size:75% position:25%
<i> and the ideology
 of disease.</i>

00:18:36.081 --> 00:18:38.083
<i> But we don't do as good
 a job, I don't think,</i>

00:18:38.183 --> 00:18:40.052 align:start size:91% position:9%
<i> in teaching them
 how to relate to the person</i>

00:18:40.152 --> 00:18:42.020
<i> who has the disease.</i>

00:18:42.120 --> 00:18:43.321 align:start position:0%
I think there was
some curiosity, like,

00:18:43.422 --> 00:18:45.457 align:start position:0% line:83%
oh, we're gonna be
reading poems

00:18:45.557 --> 00:18:47.025 align:start position:0% line:85%
and looking at art,

00:18:47.125 --> 00:18:52.331 align:start position:0% line:83%
and this is somehow
going to make us

00:18:52.431 --> 00:18:54.833 align:start position:0%
<i>doctors or something?</i>

00:18:54.933 --> 00:18:57.402 align:start size:88% position:13%
There is science to
support using humanities

00:18:57.502 --> 00:18:59.537
to help teach physicians.

00:18:59.637 --> 00:19:01.572 line:91%
One study shows that
reading literature

00:19:01.673 --> 00:19:03.641 line:91%
over nonfiction,
or pulp fiction,

00:19:03.741 --> 00:19:06.044 line:91%
can change something
called theory of mind,

00:19:06.145 --> 00:19:08.179 align:start size:84% position:16% line:91%
which is a person's
intuitive understanding

00:19:08.279 --> 00:19:11.016 align:start size:88% position:13% line:91%
of their own,
and other people's minds.

00:19:11.116 --> 00:19:13.618 align:start size:81% position:19% line:91%
Mental states,
beliefs and thoughts.

00:19:13.718 --> 00:19:16.320 line:91%
Basically, it helps us
understand ourselves

00:19:16.421 --> 00:19:18.991 align:start size:78% position:22%
and others
on a deeper level.

00:19:19.091 --> 00:19:21.092 align:start position:0% line:83%
It did show some positive
data to show that

00:19:21.193 --> 00:19:23.061 align:start position:0% line:83%
folks who read
a literary story,

00:19:23.161 --> 00:19:24.196 size:75% position:38% line:85%
changed in their ability

00:19:24.296 --> 00:19:25.797 align:start position:0% line:83%
to then judge
someone else.

00:19:25.898 --> 00:19:28.166 align:start position:0% line:83%
The hypothesis behind it,
which is really cool,

00:19:28.266 --> 00:19:31.369 size:78% position:39%
is that literary fiction
makes you think complexly

00:19:31.469 --> 00:19:32.704 size:84% position:42%
about people.

00:19:32.804 --> 00:19:34.673 align:start size:75% position:25%
<i> (Jaye)
 As does this
 iconic painting,</i>

00:19:34.773 --> 00:19:38.343 align:start size:91% position:9%
<i> whose subject appears
 to be the blonde princess.</i>

00:19:38.443 --> 00:19:41.113 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> (Dr. Furman)
 Who or what do you think
 is the subject</i>

00:19:41.213 --> 00:19:42.481
<i> of the painting.</i>

00:19:45.283 --> 00:19:47.452 align:start size:78% position:22%
<i> (Jaye)
 Until you realize
 everyone is looking</i>

00:19:47.552 --> 00:19:49.420
<i> outside the painting.</i>

00:19:49.521 --> 00:19:52.290 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> That Diego Velazquez
 has even painted himself</i>

00:19:52.390 --> 00:19:56.094
<i> into it, and he's not
 painting the princess.</i>

00:19:56.194 --> 00:19:59.630 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> It's a small detail
 that reveals the truth.</i>

00:19:59.731 --> 00:20:00.665 align:start size:75% position:25%
<i> (Dr. Furman)
 If you look
 at the painting,</i>

00:20:00.765 --> 00:20:03.234 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> right in the center of it
 is a mirror,</i>

00:20:03.335 --> 00:20:05.503
and you see two little
figures in the mirror,

00:20:05.603 --> 00:20:07.171 align:start size:81% position:19%
and those two figures
in the mirror

00:20:07.272 --> 00:20:10.442
are actually a reflection
of the king and queen.

00:20:10.542 --> 00:20:14.346 align:start size:91% position:9%
<i> (Jaye)
 As the viewer, you realize
 where you're standing.</i>

00:20:14.446 --> 00:20:17.115 align:start position:0% line:91%
<i>(Dr. Furman)
That we are in the same spot</i>

00:20:17.215 --> 00:20:19.517 align:start position:0% line:92%
<i>as the king and queen,</i>

00:20:19.617 --> 00:20:21.385 align:start position:0% line:91%
which is really
quite remarkable.

00:20:21.485 --> 00:20:22.921 align:start size:75% position:25%
<i> (Jaye)
 So how does this</i>

00:20:23.021 --> 00:20:25.489 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> relate to being
 a better psychiatrist.</i>

00:20:25.590 --> 00:20:27.559 align:start position:0%
It's easy for
physicians to say,

00:20:27.659 --> 00:20:30.061 align:start position:0%
"Ah, this is pretty clear.
You are the patient.

00:20:30.161 --> 00:20:32.063 align:start position:0%
"You are the one
with the illness."

00:20:32.163 --> 00:20:35.467 size:88% position:44%
This painting says it's much
more complicated than that.

00:20:35.567 --> 00:20:38.536 align:start position:0%
That the nature of the
relationship

00:20:38.636 --> 00:20:39.804 align:start position:0%
brings us together,

00:20:39.904 --> 00:20:41.672 align:start position:0%
and that it
de-centers us,

00:20:41.773 --> 00:20:44.376 align:start position:0%
and it makes the-the
future physician, hopefully,

00:20:44.476 --> 00:20:46.077 align:start position:0%
<i>um, think more complexly
about the nature</i>

00:20:46.177 --> 00:20:48.246 align:start position:0%
<i>of the relationship.</i>

00:20:48.346 --> 00:20:51.482 align:start size:94% position:6%
<i> (Jaye)
 The students then listen
 to the song "Strange Fruit,"</i>

00:20:51.582 --> 00:20:55.654 align:start position:0%
<i>made famous when
Billie Holiday sang it in 1939.</i>

00:20:55.754 --> 00:20:57.722 align:start size:75% position:25%
<i> It's a song
 that waxes poetic</i>

00:20:57.822 --> 00:21:00.325
<i> about scenes of
 the gallant South,</i>

00:21:00.425 --> 00:21:02.694
<i> but the title,
 "Strange Fruit,"</i>

00:21:02.794 --> 00:21:06.931
<i> refers to what's hanging
 from the poplar trees.</i>

00:21:07.031 --> 00:21:12.471
<i> ♪ Black bodies swinging
 in the sullen breeze ♪</i>

00:21:14.806 --> 00:21:16.775 align:start position:0% line:83%
You're talking about a man
who's been murdered,

00:21:16.875 --> 00:21:22.247 align:start position:0% line:83%
and, you know,
he's just strange fruit?

00:21:22.347 --> 00:21:24.649 align:start size:94% position:6%
<i> (Jaye)
 New York City school teacher
 Abel Meeropol</i>

00:21:24.749 --> 00:21:28.386 align:start size:94% position:6%
<i> wrote the song about the
 1930 lynching of Thomas Shipp</i>

00:21:28.486 --> 00:21:31.823 align:start size:81% position:19%
<i> and Abram Smith,
 the visceral contrast</i>

00:21:31.923 --> 00:21:34.792 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> between the beauty
 and cruelty of the South</i>

00:21:34.893 --> 00:21:38.496 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> speaks to the contrast
 within all of us.</i>

00:21:38.596 --> 00:21:40.831 align:start position:0%
The very ugly sides
of human nature.

00:21:40.932 --> 00:21:44.903 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> (Dr. Furman)
 And-and how absolutely
 intertwined they are.</i>

00:21:45.003 --> 00:21:48.473 align:start size:84% position:16%
Stories are enormously
complicated.

00:21:48.573 --> 00:21:50.442
<i> Enormously so.</i>

00:21:50.542 --> 00:21:54.146
And we need to wrestle with
all of those complications,

00:21:54.246 --> 00:21:57.715 align:start size:78% position:22%
<i> and this song says
 look deeper,</i>

00:21:57.816 --> 00:21:59.150
<i> look deeper,
 look deeper.</i>

00:21:59.250 --> 00:22:02.087
<i> Literally look at
 the roots of things.</i>

00:22:02.187 --> 00:22:04.689 align:start size:81% position:19%
<i> We need to
 continually do that.</i>

00:22:04.790 --> 00:22:06.858 align:start size:75% position:25%
<i> (Jaye)
 As the semester
 draws to a close,</i>

00:22:06.958 --> 00:22:10.462 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> the impact on future
 psychiatrists is evident.</i>

00:22:10.562 --> 00:22:14.333 align:start size:63% position:38%
The humanities play
a role in your life.

00:22:14.433 --> 00:22:16.734 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
I think that what this course
has allowed us to do

00:22:16.835 --> 00:22:19.771 align:start size:78% position:22% line:0%
is explore stories
in a way,

00:22:19.871 --> 00:22:22.473 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
and listen for stories
more than-

00:22:22.573 --> 00:22:24.175 line:0%
than, sort of through
our routine training

00:22:24.275 --> 00:22:25.944 line:0%
that we receive.

00:22:26.044 --> 00:22:28.046 align:start position:0%
I feel like we can
find a human story,

00:22:28.146 --> 00:22:30.181 align:start position:0%
um, everywhere.

00:22:30.281 --> 00:22:33.552 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> (Jaye)
 The arts don't just help
 make better physicians.</i>

00:22:33.652 --> 00:22:37.656 align:start size:91% position:9%
<i> They can make for a better,
 deeper human experience</i>

00:22:37.756 --> 00:22:41.159 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> in a world
 where nothing is simple.</i>

00:22:41.259 --> 00:22:42.460 align:start position:0%
Going home
and reading a poem,

00:22:42.560 --> 00:22:44.162 align:start position:0%
or going to an art museum
and seeing an art--

00:22:44.262 --> 00:22:45.363 align:start position:0%
or going-- seeing art.

00:22:45.463 --> 00:22:47.899 align:start position:0%
Or going to-to a play
and-and seeing that,

00:22:47.999 --> 00:22:49.834 align:start position:0%
or listening to music,

00:22:49.934 --> 00:22:52.604 size:81% position:41%
if you really sort of try
to involve yourself in it,

00:22:52.704 --> 00:22:54.705 align:start position:0%
it helps you look at
the world in different,

00:22:54.805 --> 00:22:57.942 align:start position:0%
more complex,
more nuanced sorts of ways,

00:22:58.043 --> 00:22:59.544 align:start position:0%
and I come from
a position where

00:22:59.644 --> 00:23:02.347 align:start position:0%
complexity and nuances
is really important.

00:23:02.447 --> 00:23:05.050 size:88% position:44%
I think making things simple
doesn't often help things.

00:23:06.151 --> 00:23:08.286
Life is moving
faster than ever.

00:23:08.386 --> 00:23:10.455 align:start size:78% position:22%
With technology
at our fingertips,

00:23:10.555 --> 00:23:12.690 align:start size:81% position:19%
and often in front of
our faces,

00:23:12.790 --> 00:23:13.692 align:start size:75% position:25%
it can sometimes
feel like

00:23:13.792 --> 00:23:15.793 align:start size:88% position:13%
we're skimming over
the surface of our lives

00:23:15.893 --> 00:23:17.428
at warp speed.

00:23:17.528 --> 00:23:20.364
Investing time and
attention in a book,

00:23:20.465 --> 00:23:22.967 align:start size:78% position:22%
or a piece of art,
or music,

00:23:23.067 --> 00:23:25.770
is an investment
that gives a return

00:23:25.870 --> 00:23:28.005
by helping us better
connect with others

00:23:28.105 --> 00:23:29.741
and ourselves.

00:23:29.841 --> 00:23:31.543
That's gonna do it
for us this week.

00:23:31.643 --> 00:23:34.813
We'll see you next time
on "Your Fantastic Mind."

00:23:36.147 --> 00:23:50.729 align:start size:6% position:94% line:0%
♪♪

